1. The Hôtel de Païva - The incredible destiny of the Mar-
quise of the Champs-Elysées
ID : 66c05fd5bfc9145a5302d53e
Title : The Hôtel de Païva - The incredible destiny of the Marquise of the Champs-Elysées
vendorId : 66c0548ebfc9145a5302d52e
description : 
The Hôtel de Païva, whose façade on the Champs Elysées is barely noticeable, is one of the most beautiful examples of private 
architecture and interior decoration under Napoleon III. It is due to the triumphant rise of one of the most noted adventurers of 
the 19th century: the Marquise de Païva. 

Let's follow in the footsteps of the most adulated courtesan of the Second Empire. I will tell you her story, her famous affairs, her 
beauty secrets.
The private mansion, which took ten years to build, now welcomes businessmen from all over the world, members of the very 
private Travellers Club. 
During the visit, I will show you the decoration of the ostentatiously luxurious lounges where marble and gilding are abundant, the 
superb onyx staircase as well as the silver-plated bronze bathtub.
Address : Avenue des Champs-Élysées 
MemberShip :bronze
Durations : 2h
StoryLine Keywords : Hôtel de Païva ,Champs Elysées ,Travellers Club ,Private Palace ,Napoleon III ,
Second Empire

2. The Perfume - What could Paris have smelled like in the 
18th century?
ID : 66c0606abfc9145a5302d53f
Title : The Perfume - What could Paris have smelled like in the 18th century?
vendorId : 66c0548ebfc9145a5302d52e
description : 
What if Paris had a smell? For some, "Paris smells of honey", "the RER B platform", "the Luxembourg gardens" and for you? 
Did you like Patrick Süskind's novel? You will love this perfumed and creative walk, the first visit in "odorama" to smell and feel the 
air of Paris with real perfume essences. They say that Parisians have a nose. Do like the hero of the book Jean-Baptiste Grenouille 
and discover the lively and enticing olfactory landscape of the largest reserve of odors in the world: the city of Paris in the 18th 
century.
This unique experience-tour invites you to relive the plot of the famous novel in the magical center of the capital. You follow in 
the footsteps of the genius from the popular district of Les Halles to the Bourgeois Paris of Saint-Germain-des-Près. Immerse 
yourself in the scents of wig powder, carriage leather, tuberoses in the carriage entrances... Inhale the fetid odors of the cemetery 
of the Innocents and the whiffs of the tanneries on the banks of the Seine. Finally, discover the arrogant voluptuousness of rococo 
perfumes...
This visit will continue in the workshop of a Parisian perfumer in a private apartment on the Ile Saint-Louis. Embark on an olfactory 
journey of 1h30. You will discover the mysteries of distillation and then train your nose to new scents. You will select those that you 
like the most and you will create, like the brilliant Jean-Baptiste Grenouille, your own perfume: a unique perfume, the one that 
suits you!
MemberShip :bronze
Durations : 2h
StoryLine Keywords : Perfume ,Les Halles ,Saint-Germain-des-Pres  ,Patrick Süskind ,Jean-Baptiste Grenouille  ,
Perfume tour ,Perfume workshop

3. Art Deco according to Jeanne Lanvin - the sumptuous 
apartment of the Parisian designer
ID : 66c061b9bfc9145a5302d541
Title : Art Deco according to Jeanne Lanvin - the sumptuous apartment of the Parisian designer
vendorId : 66c0548ebfc9145a5302d52e
description : 
22, rue du Faubourg Saint-Honoré... The legendary address of the Lanvin house, symbol of femininity and elegance, is today a 
prestigious brand recognized throughout the world. Jeanne Lanvin, a visionary designer, was also an exceptional woman. 
Born in 1867, she decided from her childhood to turn her destiny towards the fashion world. A milliner at 16, she developed a passion 
for hats. She quickly opened her own workshop and in 1925, she already employed more than 800 seamstresses. 
This visit invites you to discover a lesser-known side of the seamstress: her taste for interior decoration. 
In 1920, Jeanne Lanvin bought the former private mansion of the Marquise Arconati-Visconti, 16 rue Barbet-de-Jouy. She had 
a reception wing built whose rooms were designed by Armand-Albert Rateau. In the 1920s, this decorator developed a very 
particular style that arose from his interest in ancient art and the use of an original bestiary. 
The three rooms of Jeanne Lanvin's private apartment, also decorated by Rateau in 1924-1925, illustrate a very personal luxury 
with its furniture in bronze with an antique patina, in oak or in gilded wood. 

The visit will continue with the discovery of the "art deco" collections at the MAD (Musée des Arts Décoratifs)
Address : Musée des Arts Décoratifs
MemberShip :bronze
Durations : 2h
StoryLine Keywords : Jeanne Lanvin ,Coco Chanel ,Art Deco ,1920 ,Fashion ,
Private apartment 
5 / 62

4. Vendome Chic - The History of Haute Couture and 
Haute Joaillerie
ID : 66c06287bfc9145a5302d542
Title : Vendome Chic - The History of Haute Couture and Haute Joaillerie
vendorId : 66c0548ebfc9145a5302d52e
description : 
Cartier, Mauboussin, Van Cleef & Arpels, Boucheron… More than a century ago, these legendary Haute-joaillerie houses set up 
shop on Place Vendôme and seduced the prestigious clientele of the Ritz with their exceptional sets. Produced on site, the sublime 
pieces composed of the most sumptuous stones and diamonds attracted princesses and aristocrats from all over the world. 
Alongside them, the couturiers Frédéric Worth, Coco Chanel, Jacques Doucet, Jeanne Paquin and Paul Poiret made the coveted 
French elegance shine. Their creations, which combined audacity and tradition, called upon all the finesse of an exceptional 
Haute-couture.
A few steps further, the streets of Paix, Castiglione and Cambon have seen famous clients, icons of their eras: Marcel Proust, 
Charles Baudelaire, Jean Cocteau, Sarah Bernhardt, or Françoise Sagan… 
Thanks to a unique know-how carefully preserved and to innovative and assertive styles, these jewelers, creators and personal-
ities have contributed to building the international reputation of Paris as the capital of luxury and fashion.
Address : Place Vendome
MemberShip :bronze
Durations : 2h
StoryLine Keywords : Fashion ,Haute Couture ,Luxury Shopping ,Jewellery  ,Cartier ,Mauboussin ,
Van Cleef & Arpels ,Boucheron ,Place Vendome ,Ritz Hotel ,Frédéric Worth ,Coco Chanel ,
Marcel Proust ,Jean Cocteau

5. The legendary house of Dior
ID : 66c065a4bfc9145a5302d543
Title : The legendary house of Dior
vendorId : 66c0548ebfc9145a5302d52e
description : 
Dior, a name that rhymes with prestige, perfection and elegance. In the 50s, Christian Dior signed a fashion revival with his "Corolle" 
collection and his "New-Look" look. The couturier redesigned the body: high chest, slim waist and blossoming hips. "All of Paris" was 
stunned by this profusion of fabrics and colors. After a career as a gallery owner, illustrator and then model maker for the house 
of Lelong, he launched his own brand in February 1947. In just seven months, he created a collection that became the showcase 
of his boutique. Dior aimed for perfection, refused to restrict himself. For him, the dress is the ephemeral architecture intended 
to exalt the body of women. The gifted designer teamed up with Michel Boussac, the "king of cotton", to design increasingly long 
dresses; he gave women back their frivolity. At the end of the 1940s, the discreet man established himself as the new messiah 
of fashion. He was the first couturier to make the cover of Time magazine. His brand became the essential reference in terms of 
luxury and French chic. 
During this visit, we will focus on the store at 30 avenue Montaigne. His boutique, which has become legendary, was inspired by 
his birthplace in Granville. This family home with its understated elegance would still inspire his perfume “Miss Dior”. Today, the 
Hôtel Dior is still part of this heritage. 
For all fashion enthusiasts, come and meet the illustrious couturier with his unique creations, and discover the secrets of the house 
of Dior, synonymous with renewal, beauty and escape.
Address : Avenue Montaigne
MemberShip :silver
Durations : 2h
StoryLine Keywords : DIor ,Fashion ,Haute Couture ,Luxury Shopping ,Avenue Montaigne 
Other Experiences : ExperienceId :66c055b6bfc9145a5302d52f
ExperienceName :Private Visit of Parisian Districts
Why :Great addition to the Avenue Montaigne visit

6. Coco Chanel's Paris
ID : 66c06650bfc9145a5302d544
Title : Coco Chanel's Paris
vendorId : 66c0548ebfc9145a5302d52e
description : 
Il était une fois Gabrielle Chanel, une jeune femme qui masqua ses origines paysannes et créa sa propre légende Haute-couture, 
aidée par "Boy" Capel, son amour britannique. Symbole de l’élégance à la française dans le monde, Coco Chanel brisa les codes 
et libéra les corps de la femme moderne. 
Fondée en 1910, la maison Chanel créa la nouvelle silhouette féminine, une révolution stylistique. Les chevilles devinrent appar-
entes, la taille délivrée du corset, la peau bronzée, les cheveux coupés. Au cœur des années folles, la jeune créatrice redessina la 
silhouette de la parisienne : la tenue « sportswear chic », la fameuse petite robe noire et sa fragrance audacieuse Chanel « n°5 
». Ces pièces résistaient aux modes et au temps qui passe, la sobriété devint le gage de l’indémodable. La visite s’intéressera de 
plus près aux secrets de la rue Cambon, dans la maison Chanel, l’adresse parisienne où Coco posa ses valises en 1918 avant de 
s’installer au Ritz Place Vendôme où elle s’éteignit en 1971. 
Retraçons l’histoire de la marque Chanel, des créations de Coco aux mythiques tailleurs de Karl Lagerfeld. 
Nous aborderons également l’aspect contemporain de la marque par Virginie Viard, nouvelle créatrice de la maison Chanel. 
Redécouvrons cette maison de prestige et du luxe à la française.
MemberShip :silver
Durations : 90mins
StoryLine Keywords : Coco Chanel ,Karl Lagerfeld ,Ritz Hotel ,Fashion ,Haute Couture ,Luxury Shopping

7. The Yves Saint Laurent Museum
ID : 66c06701bfc9145a5302d545
Title : The Yves Saint Laurent Museum
vendorId : 66c0548ebfc9145a5302d52e
description : 
"The most beautiful garment that can dress a woman is the arms of the man she loves. But, for those who have not had the chance 
to find this happiness, I am here."
Meet this visionary artist, born in Algeria in 1936 and trained with the great Christian Dior. Yves-Saint-Laurent succeeded him at 
only 21 years old. He then enjoyed considerable success by founding his own brand, accompanied by Pierre Bergé, the love of his 
life.
From there, his first collections and his first fashion show were born in 1962 with his “Trapèze” dress. Feminist and committed, he 
designed the famous women’s tuxedo, inspired by the men’s wardrobe. His collections aroused interest in the midst of the sexual 
revolution. His avant-garde style liberated the woman’s body: she was, in his eyes, conquering and rebellious, like Catherine 
Deneuve. The actress became his muse and his great friend. Keen to democratize fashion, he launched his ready-to-wear line 
in 1966. Provocative, he designed his “Libération” collection in the 1970s, inspired by years of war. It caused a scandal and was 
violently criticized by the press. It still leaves its mark today. Decorated and Oscar-winning, he passed away in 2008 from a tumor. 
A look back at the unique career of this gifted designer at the Yves Saint Laurent Museum, the historic site of his former fashion 
house from 1974 to 2002. Come and admire the wealth of heritage preserved by the Pierre Bergé Foundation in the original 
atmosphere of the brand through thematic exhibitions that reflect the creative genius and the manufacturing process of the 
Haute Couture collections. 
Follow me through this unique place to meet the gifted artist and his creations preserved by the Pierre Bergé – Yves Saint Laurent 
Foundation.
MemberShip :bronze
Durations : 90 mins
StoryLine Keywords : Yves Saint Laurent ,Fashion ,Luxury Shopping ,Dior ,Avenue Montaigne

10. Hôtel de Lauzun - three centuries of history in a sump-
tuous palace
ID : 66c06a29bfc9145a5302d548
Title : Hôtel de Lauzun - three centuries of history in a sumptuous palace
vendorId : 66c0548ebfc9145a5302d52e
description : 
Who are the walkers along the banks of the Seine who know about this exceptional residence? 
Behind the heavy doors of number 17 Quai d'Anjou lies an architectural gem. Composed of a series of rooms with gilded 
decorations and ceilings comparable to those of the Château de Vaux-le-Vicomte. 
The Hôtel de Lauzun, built in 1657 for the financier Charles Grüyn des Bordes, preserves the best-preserved reception apartment 
of the Grand Siècle. This Parisian “Little Versailles” houses a unique set of opulent decorations with a thousand fancies. 
This exclusive private visit takes you into a place rarely open to the public. I will reveal its decorations to you: its superb balcony 
in gilded wrought iron, its main courtyard and its sundial, the main staircase, its splendid apartment in a row... 
I will tell you its historical secrets: the financial intrigues of the court of Louis XIV; the orgies of the Duke of Lauzun, adventurer and 
lover of the king's cousin La Grande Mademoiselle; the "artificial paradises" of Charles Baudelaire and the crazy evenings of the 
Haschichins club.
StoryLine Keywords : Ile Saint Louis ,Private Palace ,duc de Lauzun ,Charles Baudelaire 
Other Experiences : ExperienceId :66c055b6bfc9145a5302d52f
ExperienceName :Private Visit of Parisian Districts
Why :Perfect to complete the Saint Louis Island walk

12. Private Visit to the Trianon Estate
ID : 66000cff3b3a2d7cf3c2c333
Title : Private Visit to the Trianon Estate
vendorId : 65ff02c2e1b82f7ea737f8e3
description : 
In an attempt to gain some brief respite from courtly etiquette, the kings of Versailles built themselves more intimate spaces close 
to the main palace. Adjoining the Petit Parc, the estate of Trianon is home to the Grand Trianon and Petit Trianon palaces, as well 
as the Queen’s Hamlet and a variety of ornamental gardens.
Enjoy an exclusive private visit of the entire estate to discover Marie Antoinette's Petit Trianon, her intimate QUeen's Theatre and 
bucolic Hamlet set within the English Garden, and the sumptuous Napoleon apartments at the Grand Trianon when some famous 
heads of state have stayed, including those of Queen Victoria in 1855. She visited Napoleon III in 1855., Tsar Nicholas II in 1896 and 
King George VI in 1938.

13. VIP Visit of the Palace's Gardens
ID : 66000f783b3a2d7cf3c2c334
Title : VIP Visit of the Palace's Gardens
vendorId : 65ff02c2e1b82f7ea737f8e3
description : 
Visitors looking through the central window in the Hall of Mirrors will see the Grande Perspective stretching away towards the 
horizon from the Water Parterre. This unique east-west perspective originally dates from before the reign of Louis XIV, but it was 
developed and extended by the gardener André Le Nôtre, who widened the Royal Way and dug the Grand Canal. 
 
In 1661 Louis XIV entrusted André Le Nôtre with the creation and renovation of the gardens of Versailles, which he considered just 
as important as the Palace. Work on the gardens was started at the same time as the work on the palace and lasted for 40 or 
so years. During this time André Le Nôtre collaborated with the likes of Jean-Baptiste Colbert, Superintendant of Buildings to the 
King from 1664 to 1683, who managed the project, and Charles Le Brun, who was made First Painter to the King in January 1664 
and provided the drawings for a large number of the statues and fountains. Last but not least, each project was reviewed by the 
King himself, who was keen to see “every detail”. Not long after, the architect Jules Hardouin-Mansart, having been made First 
Architect to the King and Superintendant of Buildings, built the Orangery and simplified the outlines of the Park, in particular by 
modifying or opening up some of the groves. 
 
Creating the gardens was a monumental task. Large amounts of soil had to be shifted to level the ground, create parterres, 
build the Orangery and dig out the fountains and Canal in places previously occupied solely by meadows and marshes. Trees 
were brought in from different regions of France. Thousands of men, sometimes even entire regiments, took part in this immense 
project. 
 Discover the palace’s majestic gardens during a VIP visit aided by one of the head gardeners of the palace and get the privilege 
of accessing what regular visitors can’t access.
Address : Versailles
Durations : 2 hours and 30min
StoryLine Keywords : Versailles ,Royal Palace ,André Le Nôtre 
Prices : €2500 up to 10 people 
16 / 62

19. Private Visit of the Royal Tennis Court of Versailles - Jeu 
de Paume
ID : 66001e6f3b3a2d7cf3c2c33e
Title : Private Visit of the Royal Tennis Court of Versailles - Jeu de Paume
vendorId : 65ff02c2e1b82f7ea737f8e3
description : 
On 20 June 1789, the Royal Tennis Court (Jeu de Paume) of Versailles played a major part in French history. From being a royal 
sports hall during the reign of Louis XIV, it became synonymous with the foundation of French democracy and will be forever linked 
to a key episode in the French Revolution. 
 During this exclusive private visit you will discover this historical landmark where, on 20 June 1789, the deputies of the Third Estate 
met there at the time of the Estates General, and took an oath not to separate until they had endowed France with a written 
constitution. This is known as the Tennis Court Oath, which kickstarted the French Revolution.
Address : 1 Rue du Jeu de Paume, 78000 Versailles
Durations : 90 mins
StoryLine Keywords : Versailles ,French Revolution ,Real Tennis ,Jeu de Paume 
Prices : €1000

21. Private visit of the Palais Garnier
ID : 660027013b3a2d7cf3c2c341
Title : Private visit of the Palais Garnier
vendorId : 660022683b3a2d7cf3c2c340
description : 
Designed by architect Charles Garnier in 1875, the Palais Garnier hosts a prestigious auditorium and various public areas (grand 
foyer, rotonde des abonnés, lounges), as well as a museum-library and different rehearsal studios and workshops. 
 The Italian-style auditorium, with its ceiling painted in 1964 by Marc Chagall, can welcome 2054 spectators. With nearly 480,000 
visitors each year, it is one of Paris' most visited monuments. It has been listed as a historical monument since 1923.   
 During this exclusive backstage and private visit, you will discover all the famous parts of the theatre that are accessible during 
the opera’s performances without the crowds, but also, you will also get to see what the public doesn’t get to see.   The backstage 
part of the visit will take you to the opera’s stage, to the Foyer de la Danse (the Dance Foyer) behind the stage, and several other 
secretive places.
Address : Palais Garnier - Pl. de l'Opéra, 75009 Paris
Durations : 2 hour
StoryLine Keywords : Paris Opera House ,Palais Garnier ,Charles Garnier ,Opera House ,Backstage Visit 
Prices : €6500 up to 10 people

Title : The Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen
vendorId : 66017c8558cd005ba7eb4781
description : 
Inspired by the American Declaration of Independence in 1776 and the spirit of the Enlightenment, the Declaration of the Rights of 
Man and of the Citizen of 1789 marked the beginning of a new political era. Since then, it has never ceased to be a reference text. 
The French Republic explicitly states its attachment to it, citing it in the preamble of its Constitution, and the Constitutional Council 
recognized its constitutional value in 1971. 
The Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen came into existence in the summer of 1789, born of an idea of the Constituent 
Assembly, which was formed by the assembly of the Estates General to draft a new Constitution, and precede it with a declaration 
of principles.   There were many proposals. The Constituent Assembly tasked five deputies – Démeunier, La Luzerne, Tronchet, 
Mirabeau et Redon – with examining the various draft declarations, combining them into a single one and presenting it to the 
Assembly. Article by article, the French declaration was voted on between 20 and 26 August 1789. In its preamble and its 17 articles, 
it sets out the “natural and inalienable” rights, which are freedom, ownership, security, resistance to oppression; it recognizes 
equality before the law and the justice system, and affirms the principle of separation of powers. 
During this highly exclusive experience, you will get the rare privilege of seeing the original of the Declaration of the Rights of Man 
and of the Citizen, as well as several authentic preparatory drafts and historical documents. These documents are not just a 
treasure of France but of mankind.

description : 
The Prisse Papyrus is an ancient Egyptian papyrus datable to the Middle Kingdom which was discovered by the inhabitants of 
Kurna and given to French orientalist Émile Prisse d'Avennes at Thebes and published in 1847. It is the oldest known papyrus in the 
world.
Inhabitants of Kurna originally found the papyrus inside the rishi coffin of pharaoh Sekhemre-Wepmaat Intef of the 17th Dynasty, 
whose tomb was probably located in Dra' Abu el-Naga' near Thebes. The papyrus document contains the last two pages of the 
Instructions of Kagemni, who purportedly served under pharaoh Sneferu of the 4th Dynasty, and is a compilation of moral maxims 
and admonitions on the practice of virtue (sebayt). The conclusion of the Instructions of Kagemni is followed by the only complete 
surviving copy of the Instruction of Ptahhotep.

ID : 66c05f34bfc9145a5302d53d
Title : The Villa La Roche - Le Corbusier and modern architecture in Paris
vendorId : 66c0548ebfc9145a5302d52e
description : 
Let's venture into the impasse of Square du Docteur Blanche, in the 16th arrondissement. At the end of a leafy alley, hides a modern 
building with a white facade: the Maison La Roche. Built between 1923 and 1925, it is the work of the architect Le Corbusier and 
Pierre Jeanneret. You will appreciate its clean lines, far from the usual refinement of Haussmannian buildings, but which have 
nevertheless brought a new breath of life to the history of Parisian architecture. 
Its owner, the art lover Raoul La Roche, wanted a large living space to be able to display his rich collection of cubist and purist 
paintings. His friend Le Corbusier then proposed an innovative architectural project to him. He decided to use new materials, 
such as reinforced concrete and chose simple geometric shapes. His work is part of the Modern Movement and the house was 
classified as a Historic Monument in 1996. Lovers of art and architecture, you will feel at home here.
